  "prompt": "Top 10 website makers?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a list of 10 popular website builders, categorized and with a brief explanation of their strengths.  Keep in mind the \"best\" one depends heavily on your specific needs, technical skills, and budget.\n\n**All-Around Popular & User-Friendly:**\n\n1.  **Wix:**  (www.wix.com)\n    *   **Strengths:**  Extremely user-friendly drag-and-drop interface, huge template library, Wix ADI (Artificial Design Intelligence) can build a site for you based on your answers to a few questions, good for beginners and smaller businesses, a large app market.\n    *   **Considerations:** Can be harder to switch templates once your site is live, SEO can be tricky without plugins and understanding best practices, can get expensive quickly with premium plans.\n\n2.  **Squarespace:** (www.squarespace.com)\n    *   **Strengths:**  Beautiful, modern templates (arguably the most visually appealing), strong focus on design, built-in e-commerce features, reliable and secure, all-in-one platform (hosting included).  Excellent for portfolios, blogs, and online stores focused on aesthetics.\n    *   **Considerations:**  Less flexible in terms of drag-and-drop placement than Wix, can be more restrictive for advanced customization, fewer third-party apps/integrations compared to Wix or WordPress.\n\n3.  **Weebly:** (www.weebly.com)\n    *   **Strengths:**  Easy to use, drag-and-drop editor, good for simple websites and small businesses, affordable pricing, integrated e-commerce options. Owned by Square, so great integration if you use Square for payments.\n    *   **Considerations:**  Fewer design options compared to Wix or Squarespace, less advanced features, can feel limited as your needs grow.\n\n**E-Commerce Focused:**\n\n4.  **Shopify:** (www.shopify.com)\n    *   **Strengths:**  The leading e-commerce platform, specifically designed for online stores, robust inventory management, secure payment processing, marketing tools, and extensive app store. Excellent for scaling businesses.\n    *   **Considerations:**  Primarily for e-commerce; not ideal for basic informational websites, transaction fees (unless using Shopify Payments), can be more complex than other builders, steeper learning curve.\n\n5.  **BigCommerce:** (www.bigcommerce.com)\n    *   **Strengths:**  Powerful e-commerce platform, good for larger businesses and those with complex inventory or selling needs, advanced SEO features, multi-channel selling capabilities (Amazon, eBay, etc.).\n    *   **Considerations:**  More expensive than Shopify, steeper learning curve, designed for established e-commerce businesses, less user-friendly for beginners.\n\n**For More Control & Customization:**\n\n6.  **WordPress.org (Self-Hosted):** (wordpress.org)\n    *   **Strengths:**  Extremely flexible and customizable, open-source platform, thousands of themes and plugins, full control over your website, excellent for SEO, suitable for any type of website.\n    *   **Considerations:**  Requires more technical knowledge (you need to find your own hosting, install WordPress, and manage updates), steeper learning curve, more maintenance required.  **Important**:  This is different from WordPress.com, which is a hosted platform (like Wix or Squarespace).\n\n7.  **WordPress.com (Hosted):** (wordpress.com)\n    *   **Strengths:** Easier to use than self-hosted WordPress.org, but still offers a good level of customisation. You don't have to worry about hosting.\n    *   **Considerations:** Less flexible than self-hosted WordPress.org. Some of the themes and plugins aren't available. You also can't run ads on the free or cheaper plans.\n\n**Niche or Specialized:**\n\n8.  **GoDaddy Website Builder:** (www.godaddy.com/website-builder)\n    *   **Strengths:** Easy to use, good for very basic websites, integrated with GoDaddy's domain registration and hosting services, affordable.\n    *   **Considerations:** Limited design options, not as powerful or flexible as other builders, primarily for simple informational sites. Good for a very quick and easy start.\n\n9.  **Strikingly:** (www.strikingly.com)\n    *   **Strengths:** Focuses on single-page websites, very simple to use, affordable, good for personal websites, portfolios, and quick landing pages.\n    *   **Considerations:** Limited functionality, not suitable for complex websites with multiple pages, limited customization.\n\n10. **Duda:** (www.duda.co)\n     *   **Strengths:** Great for agencies and web professionals who build websites for clients. Scalable and customisable.\n     *   **Considerations:** More expensive than some of the more user-friendly options.\n\n**Key Factors to Consider When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Purpose of your website:**  Informational, e-commerce, blog, portfolio, etc.\n*   **Technical Skills:**  Are you comfortable with code and managing a server, or do you prefer a drag-and-drop interface?\n*   **Budget:**  Consider monthly subscription fees, transaction fees (for e-commerce), and the cost of themes and plugins.\n*   **Scalability:**  Will the platform be able to handle your growing needs in the future?\n*   **SEO (Search Engine Optimization):**  Does the platform offer tools and features to help you rank well in search results?\n*   **Customer Support:**  Is reliable support available if you need help?\n\n**Recommendation:**\n\n*   **Beginner looking for a simple website:** Wix, Squarespace, Weebly, GoDaddy Website Builder\n*   **E-commerce store:** Shopify, BigCommerce\n*   **Blog or highly customizable website:** WordPress.org (if you're tech-savvy), WordPress.com (if you prefer hosted)\n*   **Single-page website:** Strikingly\n*   **Web professionals building sites for clients:** Duda\n\n**Before committing to a platform, take advantage of free trials or free plans to test out the interface and features.**  Good luck!\n",
